<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="57572" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">Description</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">
Body 13-34 mm long, 2-4 mm wide, radiolar crown 6-17 mm long with 13-29 pairs of radioles, thorax with 13 chaetigers and abdomen with 46-82 chaetigers. Gregarious species (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F5999091" captionText="Figure 10. Bispira monroi (Hartman, 1961). A) Colony in situ, B) radiolar crown, C) base of crown, ventral view, D) thorax, dorsal view, E) same, ventral view, F) same, lateral view. Scale bars: A) not scaled, B, D-F) 5 mm, C) 2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e57572.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/437498" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">10</figureCitation>
A). Soft tubes constructed by fine sand. Each radiole with three purple bands without a uniform distribution pattern (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F5999091" captionText="Figure 10. Bispira monroi (Hartman, 1961). A) Colony in situ, B) radiolar crown, C) base of crown, ventral view, D) thorax, dorsal view, E) same, ventral view, F) same, lateral view. Scale bars: A) not scaled, B, D-F) 5 mm, C) 2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e57572.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/437498" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">10</figureCitation>
B). Within each purple radiolar band, there is a pair of compound eyes (three pairs of eyes per radiole). Ventral margins of thick base spiralling inwards to form three whorls (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F5999091" captionText="Figure 10. Bispira monroi (Hartman, 1961). A) Colony in situ, B) radiolar crown, C) base of crown, ventral view, D) thorax, dorsal view, E) same, ventral view, F) same, lateral view. Scale bars: A) not scaled, B, D-F) 5 mm, C) 2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e57572.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/437498" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">10</figureCitation>
C). Collar with purple spots dorsally and ventrally. Thorax with purple spots anterior to each thoracic notochaetae (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F5999091" captionText="Figure 10. Bispira monroi (Hartman, 1961). A) Colony in situ, B) radiolar crown, C) base of crown, ventral view, D) thorax, dorsal view, E) same, ventral view, F) same, lateral view. Scale bars: A) not scaled, B, D-F) 5 mm, C) 2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e57572.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/437498" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">10</figureCitation>
D). Purple maculae between ventral shields and tori (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F5999091" captionText="Figure 10. Bispira monroi (Hartman, 1961). A) Colony in situ, B) radiolar crown, C) base of crown, ventral view, D) thorax, dorsal view, E) same, ventral view, F) same, lateral view. Scale bars: A) not scaled, B, D-F) 5 mm, C) 2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e57572.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/437498" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">10</figureCitation>
E). In lateral view, dorsal and ventral spots are seen in each segment, located at the ends of notochaetae and neurochaetae (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F5999091" captionText="Figure 10. Bispira monroi (Hartman, 1961). A) Colony in situ, B) radiolar crown, C) base of crown, ventral view, D) thorax, dorsal view, E) same, ventral view, F) same, lateral view. Scale bars: A) not scaled, B, D-F) 5 mm, C) 2 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e57572.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/437498" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">10</figureCitation>
F).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="57572" type="taxon discussion">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">Taxon discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57572">
This is the only fan worm that has been included in the invertebrate guides from the Gulf of California (
<bibRefCitation author="Kerstitch, A" journalOrPublisher="Sea Challengers, Monterey" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572" refId="B5999836" refString="Kerstitch, A, Bertsch, H, 2007. Sea of Cortez Marine Invertebrates, A guide for the Pacific Coast, Mexico to Peru. Sea Challengers, Monterey" title="Sea of Cortez Marine Invertebrates, A guide for the Pacific Coast, Mexico to Peru" year="2007">Kerstitch and Bertsch 2007</bibRefCitation>
). It has been reported in the Gulf of California (
<bibRefCitation author="Kudenov, J. D." journalOrPublisher="Journal of Natural History" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572" pagination="65 - 91" refId="B5999901" refString="Kudenov, J. D., 1975. Errant polychaetes from the Gulf of California, Mexico. Journal of Natural History 9 (1): 65 - 91" title="Errant polychaetes from the Gulf of California, Mexico" volume="9" year="1975">Kudenov 1975a</bibRefCitation>
) and Pacific Panama and Costa Rica (
<bibRefCitation author="Knight-Jones, P." journalOrPublisher="Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="57572" pagination="385 - 467" refId="B5999870" refString="Knight-Jones, P., Perkins, T. H., 1998. A revision of Sabella, Bispira, and Stylomma (Polychaeta: Sabellidae. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 123: 385 - 467" title="A revision of Sabella, Bispira, and Stylomma (Polychaeta: Sabellidae" volume="123" year="1998">Knight-Jones and Perkins 1998</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
